videos.headline: Texas Tech's Gray injured on pick-and-roll collision
videos.description: Kansas' Udoka Azubuike sets the hard, but legal screen, causing a collision with Justin Gray. Gray would need assistance leaving the court to the bench.

videos.headline: Graham hits corner 3 as Kansas takes early lead
videos.description: Kansas jumps to a 13-7 lead in the first half after Devonte' Graham drills a corner triple.

videos.headline: Red Raiders fans want travel, get Jayhawks 3
videos.description: The Texas Tech crowd calls for a travel, and Kansas sharpshooter Sviatoslav Mykhailiuk silences them with a 3.

videos.headline: Graham connects with Azubuike for electric oop
videos.description: Kansas' Devonte' Graham drives and lobs it to Udoka Azubuike who throws down as the Jayhawks lead the Red Raiders 25-20.

videos.headline: Smith almost hits head on rim
videos.description: Texas Tech's Zhaire Smith defies gravity to get the tip-in around a swarm of Jayhawks.

videos.headline: Garrett erupts for #SCTop10 dunk
videos.description: Marcus Garrett drives down the lane and absolutely launches for a one-hand tomahawk jam.

videos.headline: Mykhailiuk gets shooter's bounce
videos.description: Sviatoslav Mykhailiuk hits his fourth 3-pointer of the night, getting a friendly bounce off the iron.

videos.headline: Evans' smooth assist sets up Red Raiders' layup
videos.description: Keenen Evans shows great vision to lead Norense Odiase to the basket for a layup.

videos.headline: Red Raiders not allowed in Azubuike's paint
videos.description: Zhaire Smith throws up the delicate floater but Udoka Azubuike spikes it like a volleyball for the block.

videos.headline: Evans zips down court for impressive finish
videos.description: No one can keep up with Texas Tech's Keenan Evans as he darts to the rim and hits the tough layup in traffic.

videos.headline: Graham controls body for and-1 finish
videos.description: Devonte' Graham navigates through the lane and initiates contact for the hoop and harm.

videos.headline: Culver goes coast-to-coast for posterizing slam
videos.description: Jarrett Culver gets the rebound and takes it all the way himself for the two-handed jam over Mitch Lightfoot.

videos.headline: Beautiful bounce pass sets up Kansas triple
videos.description: Devonte' Graham fires a cross-court bounce pass to Malik Newman for the 3-pointer.

videos.headline: TTU VS KU
Culver keeps Red Raiders alive with cold-blooded triple
videos.description: Texas Tech trails Kansas 67-64 after Jarrett Culver shoots the 3 without hesitation.

videos.headline: Texas Tech ties it on insane Smith putback
videos.description: Zhaire Smith is playing the entire game above the rim with a crazy display of athleticism on the putback finish to tie the game at 68-68.

videos.headline: Smith delivers on D with huge block
videos.description: Devonte' Graham has a wide-open dunk under the basket but Zhaire Smith flashes in to get the block and keep the game tied.

videos.headline: Kansas regains lead on clutch Graham jumper
videos.description: Devonte' Graham gets to his spot and sinks the clutch jumper to give the Jayhawks a 70-68 lead.

videos.headline: Graham's prayer falls to extend Kansas lead
videos.description: Devonte' Graham does it all himself on the drive with an acrobatic finish to put the Jayhawks up 72-68 with under a minute left.

videos.headline: Graham the star as Kansas holds on
videos.description: Devonte' Graham hit clutch shot after clutch shot in the 2nd half, saying he "just wanted to win" and had to stay aggressive.

article.description: Devonte Graham scored 26 points and No. 8 Kansas set an NCAA record with its 14th straight regular-season conference championship, clinching at least a tie for the Big 12 title with a 74-72 victory against sixth-ranked Texas Tech on Saturday.

video.headline: Graham, Mykhailiuk help Kansas hold off TTU
video.caption: Devonte' Graham tallies a game-high 26 points and Sviatoslav Mykhailiuk adds 21 points in the Jayhawks' 74-72 win over Texas Tech.

article.headline: Kansas sets NCAA record with 14th straight regular-season league title

images.name: Graham, Mykhailiuk help Kansas hold off TTU
images.caption: Devonte' Graham tallies a game-high 26 points and Sviatoslav Mykhailiuk adds 21 points in the Jayhawks' 74-72 win over Texas Tech.

article.linkText: Kansas earns record 14th straight league title
article.story:
LUBBOCK, Texas -- Devonte' Graham barged through a door with a big smile, wearing a hat tilted slightly forward over his eyes that read "14 straight.''

Kansas finally has its NCAA record.

Graham scored 26 points and the eighth-ranked Jayhawks wrapped up their 14th consecutive regular-season conference championship, clinching at least a tie for the Big 12 title with a 74-72 victory against sixth-ranked Texas Tech on Saturday.

"It's just being a part of history and me and my boy are part of it," Graham said as he turned toward fellow senior Sviatoslav Mykhailiuk, who scored 21.

Graham hit a tiebreaking jumper with 1:30 remaining to help Kansas (23-6, 12-4) to its fourth straight win and a two-game lead over the Red Raiders, who have lost three in a row for the first time this season. The Jayhawks never trailed.

All 14 of the titles have come under coach Bill Self, who finished second in his first season at KU. Four of the previous 13 championships were shared. UCLA won 13 straight Pac-10 titles from 1967 to 1979.

"We picked the best time to be our best the last couple of weeks,'' Self said. "To play with little depth and to play so small and to not be a physical team at all, to see how these guys hung in there and competed, I'm amazed."

The current skid for the Red Raiders (22-7, 10-6) started when leading scorer Keenan Evans injured a toe in the first half of a loss to Baylor that pulled Kansas even in the Big 12 race. The senior guard scored six points in his third straight game in single digits since the injury.

Zhaire Smith scored 20 points and fellow freshman Jarrett Culver had 18 for Texas Tech, which dropped its second straight game since reaching the highest ranking in school history. The Red Raiders surpassed last week's No. 7 ranking that matched the 1995-96 team.

"You've got to credit the opponent,'' coach Chris Beard said. "It's why their players, a lot of them, go to the NBA. It's why they win our conference almost every year, or every year, not almost. We were part of the fight. And we intend to be part of the fight as we build the program."

The Jayhawks scored the first eight points and led by eight with less than five minutes remaining after Graham hit a long 3 with the shot clock about to expire. But just like the rest of the season in the rugged Big 12, it wasn't easy.

Smith had a putback dunk to pull Texas Tech even at 68-68 before Graham hit the go-ahead jumper and got an off-balance shot to fall while the Red Raiders committed turnovers on consecutive possessions.

After a throw-in to run off the final two seconds, the Jayhawks stormed the court to the cheers of scattered fans in blue in what had been a raucous arena. Texas Tech students camped overnight for a national TV event the morning of the game.

"I feel like this year was the year that everybody thought we were going to lose it," Graham said. "As a team, we've just been battling, staying positive with each other, going through the grind. And now we made history."

BIG PICTURE

Kansas: Mykhailiuk and Graham formed a pretty good first half-second half tag team. The Ukrainian guard had a team-leading 15 points and three assists before halftime, and Graham had 18 points in the second half.

Texas Tech: The Red Raiders are trying to get as much out of Evans as possible, subbing him frequently to rest the injured toe. But his impact clearly isn't the same, and whether the toe improves is likely to determine how far Tech goes in the NCAA tournament.

TOP-10 WINS

Kansas is 3-0 against top-10 teams this season and has won eight straight true road games against top-10 opponents. The last loss was to No. 4 Missouri on Feb. 2, 2012.

SMITH IN, GRAY OUT

Texas Tech senior Zach Smith entered in the first minute after missing 13 games with a broken foot. He replaced Justin Gray, who was flattened when he didn't see a screen by 7-foot, 280-pound Udoka Azubuike. Gray stayed down for a couple of minutes before walking slowly to the bench. Gray didn't return, and Smith finished with one point and four rebounds in 22 minutes.

UP NEXT

Kansas: Home against Texas on Monday before its regular-season finale at Oklahoma State next Saturday.

Texas Tech: At No. 21 West Virginia on Monday before finishing the regular season at home against TCU next Saturday. The Red Raiders and Mountaineers are tied for second in the Big 12.
